---

## What is different from main

The main branch is conservative. If an offset is not confirmed from hardware or an Intel document, it does not write. ME 18 (Meteor Lake) exits with a clear warning and leaves the image untouched.

This branch is for people who understand the risk and want to help push the research forward. Specifically it adds diagnostic output for MTL that dumps the IOE Soft Straps region so you can share the data and help confirm the HAP offset.

**For ME 12 through ME 16.1, the two branches are functionally identical.** All confirmed offsets are the same. If you are on an 8th–13th gen platform use either branch — they produce the same output.

---

## The MTL Problem

Meteor Lake dropped the discrete PCH entirely. The flash descriptor layout changed completely with the tile architecture. On every previous platform going back to 8th gen, the PCH Straps live at `fpsba = 0x100` and the HAP bit is in a known PCHSTRP register. On MTL none of that applies.

What we know:
- No PCH Straps at `0x100`
- IOE Soft Straps region starts around `0xCAC` in the descriptor
- HAP is almost certainly in that region, at a specific dword and bit — but which one has not been confirmed from a real MTL firmware dump

What we do not know:
- The exact dword offset within the IOE Soft Straps region
- Whether it is still bit 16 of that dword, or a different bit
- Whether the offset is the same across all MTL SKUs

Writing a random guess to the IOE Soft Straps region on a real machine could corrupt the firmware image. This branch will not do that.

---

## How to Help Confirm the MTL Offset

If you have a Meteor Lake machine (Core Ultra 100 or 200 series, 14th gen) and are comfortable with firmware tooling, here is how to contribute:

**Method 1 — Intel FIT (requires Windows)**

1. Dump your BIOS with flashrom: `sudo flashrom -p internal -r stock.bin`
2. Open the dump in Intel Flash Image Tool (FIT), enable the HAP/AltMeDisable option under ME settings, save the output image
3. Run the diff tool: `python3 hap_diff.py stock.bin fit_output.bin`
4. Open an issue with the output

**Method 2 — BIOS toggle (if your BIOS exposes it)**

Some MTL BIOSes have an ME disable option under advanced settings. If yours does:

1. Dump BIOS before enabling it: `sudo flashrom -p internal -r before.bin`
2. Enable ME disable in BIOS, reboot, dump again: `sudo flashrom -p internal -r after.bin`
3. Run: `python3 hap_diff.py before.bin after.bin`
4. Open an issue with the output

**What hap_diff.py does:** it filters out all the noise FIT makes (checksum updates, version counters, provisioning blocks) and focuses specifically on changes in the IOE strap region, reporting the exact offset and bit that changed. One person with a dump is all it takes to confirm this.

The `hap_diff.py` tool is in the [ifdtool-thinkpad](https://github.com/MangoKiwiPlumGrape/ifdtool_thinkpad) repo.

---

## HAP Locations — Current Status

| ME Version | Platform | HAP Location | Status |
|---|---|---|---|
| ME 12 LP | 8th/9th gen (Cannon/Whiskey/Coffee Lake U) | PCHSTRP28 — `fpsba+0x70` bit 16 | Confirmed |
| ME 12 H | 8th/9th gen desktop (Z390/H370/B360) | PCHSTRP32 — `fpsba+0x80` bit 16 | Confirmed |
| ME 13 | 10th gen Ice Lake LP | PCHSTRP28 — `fpsba+0x70` bit 16 | Confirmed |
| ME 14 | 10th gen Comet Lake LP | PCHSTRP28 — `fpsba+0x70` bit 16 | Confirmed |
| ME 15 LP | 11th gen Tiger Lake LP | PCHSTRP31 — `fpsba+0x7C` bit 16 | Confirmed |
| ME 15 H | 11th/12th gen TGL-H / RKL-H | PCHSTRP37 — `fpsba+0x94` bit 16 | Confirmed |
| ME 16 | 12th gen Alder Lake | PCHSTRP31 — `fpsba+0x7C` bit 16 | Confirmed |
| ME 16.1 | 13th gen Raptor Lake | PCHSTRP31 — `fpsba+0x7C` bit 16 | Confirmed |
| ME 18 | 14th gen Meteor Lake | IOE Soft Straps ~`0xCAC` + unknown offset | **Research — write skipped** |

---

## Usage

Identical to main. The only difference you will see on a non-MTL machine is the branch name in comments.

```bash
# Check HAP state
python3 me_cleaner_experimental.py -c your_dump.bin

# Set HAP bit
python3 me_cleaner_experimental.py -s your_dump.bin -O patched.bin
```

On an MTL machine, instead of writing, the tool will print the IOE Soft Straps region contents and instructions for sharing the data.

---

## What Goes into Main

Once an MTL HAP offset is confirmed from a real dump — either through this research or from someone else — it gets added to both branches simultaneously and the experimental branch moves on to the next unconfirmed platform (ARL, LNL, PTL).

Confirmed data only ever goes into main. Guesses stay in experimental until proven.

